🧠 B. One Night At Freddy’s — Notes
🔹 Problem Simplification
We have m animatronics (counters)
Each second → +1 added to exactly one
At times a[i] → we can reset one counter to 0
Goal → minimize:
max(d1, d2, ..., dm) at time l
🔥 Core Idea
👉 Worst case:

Adversary tries to increase the same animatronic repeatedly

👉 Our control:

We can:

distribute increments across multiple animatronics
reset the largest one at given times
💡 Key Transformation

Instead of thinking about animatronics:

👉 Think:

Maintain k counters (active ones)

Where:

k = min(m, remaining_resets + 1)
⚡ Greedy Strategy

At every second:

1. Increment smallest counter
→ balances growth
2. At reset time:
→ reset largest counter
3. Update active counters:
k = min(k, remaining_resets + 1)
🧠 Why this works
Incrementing smallest → avoids one counter blowing up
Resetting largest → removes worst danger
Limiting k → optimal number of active threats

👉 This is load balancing + greedy reset

🔄 Simulation Flow

For each second d = 1 → l:

v[0]++ (smallest grows)
Sort → maintain order
If d is reset:
v[k-1] = 0 (kill largest)
decrease available resets
update k
💻 Code (Clean Version)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

#define fast_io ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);

void solve() {
    int n, m, l;
    cin >> n >> m >> l;

    vector<int> a(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> a[i];

    int k = min(n + 1, m);
    vector<int> v(k, 0);

    int idx = 0; // pointer for reset times

    for (int d = 1; d <= l; d++) {
        // 1. increment smallest
        v[0]++;
        sort(v.begin(), v.begin() + k);

        // 2. reset if needed
        if (idx < n && a[idx] == d) {
            v[k - 1] = 0;
            idx++;

            // update k
            k = min(k, n - idx + 1);

            sort(v.begin(), v.begin() + k);
        }
    }

    cout << v[k - 1] << '\n';
}

int main() {
    fast_io;
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--) solve();
}
⏱ Complexity
Per test case:
Loop runs l times
Each step:
sort size k ≤ m

👉 Complexity:

O(l * m log m)
Given constraint:
Σ (m * l) ≤ 2e5

👉 So overall:

≈ O(2e5 log m) ✅ safe
🔥 Key Observations (Revision)
Only smallest grows → prevents imbalance
Always reset largest → greedy optimal
k = min(m, remaining_resets + 1) → critical trick
Final answer = largest counter
